{"action": "edit", "code": "def find_teal_lines(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> List[List[Tuple[int, int]]]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Given an input grid, this function returns a list of lists, where each inner list contains the coordinates of \n    the teal pixels that form a horizontal or vertical line.\n    \n    Parameters:\n    input_grid (np.ndarray): A 2D numpy array representing the input grid.\n    \n    Returns:\n    List[List[Tuple[int,int]]]: A list of lists, where each inner list contains the coordinates of the teal pixels \n    that form a horizontal or vertical line.\n    \"\"\"\n    lines = []\n    for i in range(input_grid.shape[0]):\n        line = []\n        for j in range(input_grid.shape[1]):\n            if input_grid[i][j] == teal:\n                line.append((i, j))\n        if len(line) > 1:\n            lines.append(line)\n    for j in range(input_grid.shape[1]):\n        line = []\n        for i in range(input_grid.shape[0]):\n            if input_grid[i][j] == teal:\n                line.append((i, j))\n        if len(line) > 1:\n            lines.append(line)\n    return lines\ndef main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    output_grid = input_grid.copy()\n    lines = find_teal_lines(input_grid)\n    red = find_non_connected_red_pixels(input_grid)\n    output_grid = connect_singletons_to_lines(lines, red, output_grid)\n    return output_grid\ndef connect_singletons_to_lines(lines: List[List[Tuple[int, int]]], singletons: List[Tuple[int, int]], grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    Given a list of lists containing the coordinates of the teal pixels that form a horizontal or vertical line, a list \n    of coordinates of the red pixels that are not connected to any of the teal lines, and a 2D numpy array representing \n    the input grid, this function connects each of the singleton blocks to each of the lines by making a line of color y \n    perpendicular the lines of color x. It changes the color of the line blocks where the new line touches, and surrounds \n    each block that has been to color y with blocks of color x.\n    \n    Parameters:\n    lines (List[List[Tuple[int,int]]]): A list of lists containing the coordinates of the teal pixels that form a \n    horizontal or vertical line.\n    singletons (List[Tuple[int,int]]): A list of coordinates of the red pixels that are not connected to any of the \n    teal lines.\n    grid (np.ndarray): A 2D numpy array representing the input grid.\n    \n    Returns:\n    np.ndarray: A 2D numpy array representing the output grid.\n    \"\"\"\n    output_grid = grid.copy()\n    for singleton in singletons:\n        closest_line = None\n        closest_distance = float('inf')\n        for line in lines:\n            for pixel in line:\n                distance = abs(singleton[0] - pixel[0]) + abs(singleton[1] - pixel[1])\n                if distance < closest_distance:\n                    closest_distance = distance\n                    closest_line = line\n        if closest_line[0][0] == closest_line[1][0]:\n            output_grid[singleton[0]][singleton[1]] = yellow\n            for i in range(min(closest_line[0][1], closest_line[1][1]), max(closest_line[0][1], closest_line[1][1]) + 1):\n                if output_grid[singleton[0]][i] == blue:\n                    output_grid[singleton[0]][i] = green\n        else:\n            output_grid[singleton[0]][singleton[1]] = yellow\n            for i in range(min(closest_line[0][0], closest_line[1][0]), max(closest_line[0][0], closest_line[1][0]) + 1):\n                if output_grid[i][singleton[1]] == blue:\n                    output_grid[i][singleton[1]] = green\n    return output_grid\ndef find_non_connected_red_pixels(input_grid: np.ndarray, lines: List[List[Tuple[int, int]]]) -> List[Tuple[int, int]]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Given an input grid and a list of lists containing the coordinates of the teal pixels that form a horizontal or \n    vertical line, this function returns a list of coordinates of the red pixels that are not connected to any of the \n    teal lines.\n    \n    Parameters:\n    input_grid (np.ndarray): A 2D numpy array representing the input grid.\n    lines (List[List[Tuple[int,int]]]): A list of lists containing the coordinates of the teal pixels that form a \n    horizontal or vertical line.\n    \n    Returns:\n    List[Tuple[int,int]]: A list of coordinates of the red pixels that are not connected to any of the teal lines.\n    \"\"\"\n    non_connected_red_pixels = []\n    for i in range(input_grid.shape[0]):\n        for j in range(input_grid.shape[1]):\n            if input_grid[i][j] == red:\n                connected = False\n                for line in lines:\n                    if (i, j) in line:\n                        connected = True\n                        break\n                if not connected:\n                    non_connected_red_pixels.append((i, j))\n    return non_connected_red_pixels", "user_code": "def main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    output_grid = input_grid.copy()\n    lines = `find the several horizontal or ventical lines of teal pixels `(input_grid)\n    red = `find the several singleton pixels of red color non connected with the lines`(input_grid)\n    output_grid = `Make a line of color y perpendicular the lines of color x to connect each of the singleton blocks to each of the lines. Change the color of the line blocks where the new line touches, surround each block that has been to color y with blocks of color x. Done.`(lines, red, output_grid)\n    return output_grid", "gpt_code": "def find_teal_lines(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> List[List[Tuple[int, int]]]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Given an input grid, this function returns a list of lists, where each inner list contains the coordinates of \n    the teal pixels that form a horizontal or vertical line.\n    \n    Parameters:\n    input_grid (np.ndarray): A 2D numpy array representing the input grid.\n    \n    Returns:\n    List[List[Tuple[int,int]]]: A list of lists, where each inner list contains the coordinates of the teal pixels \n    that form a horizontal or vertical line.\n    \"\"\"\n    lines = []\n    for i in range(input_grid.shape[0]):\n        line = []\n        for j in range(input_grid.shape[1]):\n            if input_grid[i][j] == teal:\n                line.append((i, j))\n        if len(line) > 1:\n            lines.append(line)\n    for j in range(input_grid.shape[1]):\n        line = []\n        for i in range(input_grid.shape[0]):\n            if input_grid[i][j] == teal:\n                line.append((i, j))\n        if len(line) > 1:\n            lines.append(line)\n    return lines\ndef connect_singletons_to_lines(lines: List[List[Tuple[int, int]]], singletons: List[Tuple[int, int]], grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    Given a list of lists containing the coordinates of the teal pixels that form a horizontal or vertical line, a list \n    of coordinates of the red pixels that are not connected to any of the teal lines, and a 2D numpy array representing \n    the input grid, this function connects each of the singleton blocks to each of the lines by making a line of color y \n    perpendicular the lines of color x. It changes the color of the line blocks where the new line touches, and surrounds \n    each block that has been to color y with blocks of color x.\n    \n    Parameters:\n    lines (List[List[Tuple[int,int]]]): A list of lists containing the coordinates of the teal pixels that form a \n    horizontal or vertical line.\n    singletons (List[Tuple[int,int]]): A list of coordinates of the red pixels that are not connected to any of the \n    teal lines.\n    grid (np.ndarray): A 2D numpy array representing the input grid.\n    \n    Returns:\n    np.ndarray: A 2D numpy array representing the output grid.\n    \"\"\"\n    output_grid = grid.copy()\n    for singleton in singletons:\n        closest_line = None\n        closest_distance = float('inf')\n        for line in lines:\n            for pixel in line:\n                distance = abs(singleton[0] - pixel[0]) + abs(singleton[1] - pixel[1])\n                if distance < closest_distance:\n                    closest_distance = distance\n                    closest_line = line\n        if closest_line[0][0] == closest_line[1][0]:\n            output_grid[singleton[0]][singleton[1]] = yellow\n            for i in range(min(closest_line[0][1], closest_line[1][1]), max(closest_line[0][1], closest_line[1][1]) + 1):\n                if output_grid[singleton[0]][i] == blue:\n                    output_grid[singleton[0]][i] = green\n        else:\n            output_grid[singleton[0]][singleton[1]] = yellow\n            for i in range(min(closest_line[0][0], closest_line[1][0]), max(closest_line[0][0], closest_line[1][0]) + 1):\n                if output_grid[i][singleton[1]] == blue:\n                    output_grid[i][singleton[1]] = green\n    return output_grid\ndef find_non_connected_red_pixels(input_grid: np.ndarray, lines: List[List[Tuple[int, int]]]) -> List[Tuple[int, int]]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Given an input grid and a list of lists containing the coordinates of the teal pixels that form a horizontal or \n    vertical line, this function returns a list of coordinates of the red pixels that are not connected to any of the \n    teal lines.\n    \n    Parameters:\n    input_grid (np.ndarray): A 2D numpy array representing the input grid.\n    lines (List[List[Tuple[int,int]]]): A list of lists containing the coordinates of the teal pixels that form a \n    horizontal or vertical line.\n    \n    Returns:\n    List[Tuple[int,int]]: A list of coordinates of the red pixels that are not connected to any of the teal lines.\n    \"\"\"\n    non_connected_red_pixels = []\n    for i in range(input_grid.shape[0]):\n        for j in range(input_grid.shape[1]):\n            if input_grid[i][j] == red:\n                connected = False\n                for line in lines:\n                    if (i, j) in line:\n                        connected = True\n                        break\n                if not connected:\n                    non_connected_red_pixels.append((i, j))\n    return non_connected_red_pixels", "holes": {"find_teal_lines": "find the several horizontal or ventical lines of teal pixels ", "connect_singletons_to_lines": "Make a line of color y perpendicular the lines of color x to connect each of the singleton blocks to each of the lines. Change the color of the line blocks where the new line touches, surround each block that has been to color y with blocks of color x. Done.", "find_non_connected_red_pixels": "find the several singleton pixels of red color non connected with the lines"}}
